<font color="#FF0000">THE DIVINE WARRIOR IN VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 10 18:54:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Class Lass, <br>
Your parents views about the President being God’s representative comes from Paul’s letter to the Romans where he points out That we ought to subject ourselves to governing authorities. For there is no authority except from God, and those authorities that exist are in deed established by God. <br><br>
What we need to bear in mind was that those invested with such awesome responsibilities were so elected for the good of all people and if they fail to carry out their responsibilities righteously they and their nations become subject to God’s eternal judgement. God calls these selfish and self serving leaders: hidden reefs, feasting without fear, caring for themselves; clouds without water, carried along by winds; autumn trees without fruit, doubly dead, uprooted; wild waves of the sea, casting up their own shame like the foam of the sea; wandering stars, for whom the black darkness of hell has been reserved forever (Romans 13:1-3, Jude 1:12-13).<br><br>
Is this why our nation suffered such a disgrace in Vietnam? Because our President and the leaders that advised him were not right in serving those who had entrusted them with such great responsibility? Because they thought of their own political standing above the needs of our nation and the nation who had called upon us for help? A nation who’s own President was engaged in his own foolish and selfish desires for wealth and power?<br><br>
While I still want to answer some of the other issues brought up by others here, bear with me as I share with you some notes I wrote down concerning the your primary thoughts, in the next post.<br><br>
Class Lass you wrote; <br><br>
“How we can know whose side God is on when opposing sides claim that status. <br>
I am not the only one whose attitudes have changed toward organized religion. Some people have turned their back on all religions. Some people have changed their philosophy and follow the oriental philosophy such as one of the Buddisms, or Hinduism. Some people have found peace in the Indian way of life and thought. How have your attitudes changed toward your basic cultural/religious belief's as a result of your service in Vietnam? -- (ClassLass)”<br><br>
Class Lass Here are my thoughts concerning what you have posted above, as a Vietnam veteran and now as a Christian pastor. <br><br>
“Whose side God is on when opposing sides claim that status?”<br><br>
Did the Buddhist Monks in Vietnam call upon their gods to fight against us and against American intervention in their country? Did we not at the same time call upon our God to protect us in battle? Some of the Viet Cong we fought against may have been Buddhist or even Catholics, while the NVA soldier with their communistic goals would not lend to a religious belief did that, make killing them more acceptable? It did to me, especially after I saw what destruction and the vicious way they killed South Vietnamese citizens. <br><br>
The Samaritans were a religious lot who worshipped the same God of Israel but they would not accept Jesus as their Messiah because he was on his way to celebrate the Passover feast in Jerusalem. They believed that God’s place of worship was mount Gerizim not Jerusalem. <br>
&quot;Our fathers worshiped in this mountain, and you {people} say that in Jerusalem is the place where men ought to worship.&quot; (John 4:20, Luke 9:51-56) <br>
The Jews would have no dealings with the Samaritans, nor they with them. The Samaritans who also worshipped other gods were not privileged to know what Jesus had to accomplish in Jerusalem; they did not know the operational orders His Father had issued.<br>
 <br>
The Lord’s disciples James and John who had once before tried to advance in rank through improper military channels now desired to wipe out the Samaritans by calling in artillery and raining napalm upon them from heaven. <br><br>
&quot;Lord, do You want us to command fire to come down from heaven and consume them?&quot; The Lord rebuked them, and said, <br>
&quot;You do not know what kind of spirit you are of; for the Son of Man did not come to destroy men's lives, but to save them.&quot;(Luke 9:53-56). <br><br>
But when I first began my inner spiritual journey trying to find and to satisfy that hunger within and to fill that hole Vietnam had left inside of me, I could not reconcile this God of love with the one I read about in the Old Testament. To me the God of the Old Testament was a Marine, guts and glory and all that. I did not understand the God of love and how the two could be engaged in the same mission. But it wasn’t long before I realized “The violence of God can only be understood in the shadow of the Cross” (see above post).<br><br>
 <br>
The Lord did not tell James and John that they did not have the authority as soldiers to call in artillery, to rain fire and brimstone upon the Samaritans but only that they had a wrong spirit in desiring to destroy the city, for all the wrong reason. But then again there were times in Nam when I wanted to destroy whole villages just to avenge the death of someone I cared about. <br><br>
Yet, in the scriptures I had found the God who claimed to be the author of creation also depicted in very violent ways. He is often described as a Warring God who uses individuals, nations and nature to annihilate his enemies. <br><br>
This Divine Warrior often delivered Israel from her enemies using the Israelites as his chosen warriors, yet just as often he used Israel’s enemies to bring judgement upon his own chosen people because of their disobedience, waywardness and for whoring after false gods.<br>
 <br>
But it’s in the scriptures that we find that those who have been entrusted to fight God’s battles are also required to follow strong moral convictions. That God requires his warriors to ascribe to certain codes of conduct, to follow His precepts or suffer the consequences of His wrath.<br><br>
The first time we encounter this warrior God arrayed in His battle dress is when he started the war against the Egyptian nation who had enslaved, then began killing the Israelite’s male children just as soon as they were born.  <br><br>
What unfolds afterwards is the establishment of a military institution. As this new nation under God’s promised protection begins to emerge and begins to trust in him we see them become the Army he will use to win His battles. We find them encamped as a massive Army with their tribal tents pitched in ranks and arranged in marching order. Their household standards and unique proud colorful banners flying overhead before each company of people. We find them arranged by their officers and captains by rank, by hundreds and by thousands with a commander–in chief in charge. The presence of God overshadowing them as a cloud by day and as they break camp you would hear the cadence of their trust and believe in their God, as they moved out and sang with a great outcry: <br>
&quot;Rise up, O LORD! And let Thine enemies be scattered, and let those who hate Thee flee before Thee&quot; (Num 10:34-36). <br><br>
Against incredible odds battles are fought and won. Little Israel against powerful Egypt.  Gideon’s small band of army against the Midionites, David against Goliath. What do we learn from all this? That God’s people were the strongest when they were the weakest it was when they submitted themselves to God and allowed Him to lead them that they won their great battles. <br><br>
American once was known as a powerful Christian nation, but it all changed in the sixties. Leaders of the world who had send their princes and their children to our universities to be educated, expected to encounter Christian beliefs and principles but instead found Marx and communism being propagated. Instead of the love of Jesus, they found a different kind of free love, and a break down of our nations moral character. Today I see the wrath of God being held in check only by His grace. Yet I feel he remains lock and loaded waiting for us to continue in our present path of destructive compromise which will soon command His intervention and His form of justice.  <br><br>
I had often found it hard to reconcile a loving God with the warrior God depicted in the Old Testament. How can this be a loving God? How could he command the total destruction of all the residence of the cities His chosen people were to inherit? <br>
Livestock, men, women, children and sucking babies, he commanded that it all be destroyed. Even Joshua their commander-in-chief burned down cities (The original zippo lighter)and they all struck every man with the edge of the sword, until they had destroyed them all. They left no one who breathed. (Deut 20:16-18, Josh 11:13-14).<br><br>
No Geneva cards were issued, no mercy given to the enemy, but the genocide of several nations was accomplished.  <br><br>
Today many would condemn God for issuing such commands. When we do, we fail to remember that those same nations had their own gods who could not see, hear, speak or serve their people. That those nations of people would try to appease their gods by going out and destroying other people and annihilating all manner of life. They would have destroyed God’s people much like the Arabs would like to destroy Israel today. Those nations were identified, as godless nations (the communist of those times) whom God declared should be destroyed because of the sins they had committed. They often offered their own sons and daughters as sacrifices to those gods. I shudder to think what great wrath is in stored for this nation for our condoning, accepting and supporting the abortion of our own children.  <br><br>
Israel in the fields of battle only prospered when their hands were clean, when they waged war with Holy hands. When they plundered for personal gain and when they trusted in their weapons, strength and numbers instead of in their God they always suffered defeat. Today we trust not in God but in our smart weapons of mass destruction. <br><br>
A battle is yet to be fought but I find we may not have any warriors to fight that battle, <br><br>
“Listen... The LORD of hosts is mustering the army for battle… Behold, the day of the LORD is coming, cruel, with fury and burning anger, to make the land a desolation; and He will exterminate its sinners from it. Isaiah  13:4-9<br>

